# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gatling-gun
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] Developed for self defense, the modern .22 short, though still used in a few pocket pistols and mini-revolvers, is mainly used as a quiet round for practice by the recreational shooter.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] The .22 short was popularly used in shooting galleries at fairs and arcades; several rifle makers produced "gallery" models for .22 short exclusively.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] Due to its low recoil and good inherent accuracy, the .22 short was used for the Olympic 25 meter rapid fire pistol event until 2004, and it was allowed in the shooting part of modern pentathlon competitions before they switched to air pistols.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] Several makes of starter pistols use .22 short blank cartridges.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] Some powder-actuated nail guns use .22 short blanks as a power source.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] Most .22 short bullets are made of lead (usually coated with grease or wax, or copper) in round nose or hollow point styles.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] Bullets for use at shooting galleries were often made of compressed powdered metal that disintegrated on impact to avoid ricochets and over-penetration of backstops.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] The standard velocity .22 short launches a 29-grain (1.9 g) bullet at 1,045 feet per second (319 m/s) with 70 ft·lbf (95 J) of energy from a 22 in (559 mm) rifle barrel and can penetrate 2 inches (51 mm) of soft pine.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] As a hunting round, the high velocity hollow point Short is useful only for small game such as tree squirrels and rabbits.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] For small game hunting in general, the greater energy and wider ammunition selection of the .22 long rifle make it a more popular choice.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] In the American South, the .22 short hollow point is still very popular for use on raccoons, which are treed at night using dogs and shooting is at close range.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] In some states, the .22 short is the only legal round to use for such hunting.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] Although the .22 long rifle has surpassed the .22 short in the marketplace, many ammunition companies still produce .22 shorts, and in a fairly wide variety.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] Most makers utilize the standard 29-grain (1.9 g) solid round nose bullet and 27-grain (1.7 g) hollow point bullet weights for the .22 short.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] Several types are made by CCI: a CB Short at 727 ft/s (222 m/s), target Shorts at 830 ft/s (250 m/s), their standard Short round with plated round nose bullet at 1,080 ft/s (330 m/s), and a high speed hunting load with plated hollow point bullet at 1,105 ft/s (337 m/s).
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] The .22 short high-velocity exceeds the performance of the .22 long (with the exception of CCI's High Velocity 1217fps long loading), and the .22 short has displaced the .22 long as an alternate to the .22 long rifle for many .22 shooters.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] Fiocchi makes their Exacta Compensated Super Match SM200 with lead round nose at 650 ft/s (200 m/s).
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] Remington produces a high velocity plated round nose at 1,095 ft/s (334 m/s).
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] Aguila makes both a match lead round nose at 1,095 ft/s (334 m/s), and a "high speed" round with plated bullet also listed at 1,095 ft/s (334 m/s).
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] Also available is the RWS R25 match ammunition at 560 ft/s (170 m/s).
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] Eley also makes their rapid fire match cartridge at 750 ft/s (230 m/s).
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] Most of the target oriented and CB Shorts are very quiet, due to being subsonic.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] When fired from a full-length rifle barrel, most .22 short loadings are as quiet as if not quieter than, the average air rifle.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] There have been many rifles chambered for the .22 short over the years, but only several lever action rifles are currently chambered for this round, notably Henry Repeating Arms and Marlin Firearms Co. lever action rifles.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] The Marlin Golden 39A model represents the oldest and longest continuously produced shoulder firearm in the world.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] Many rifles in .22 short were made between 1901 and 1940, mostly intended for gallery shooting and small game hunting.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] Remington and Winchester produced the most rifles in .22 short.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] Remington has made their Model 24 and Model 241 "Speedmaster" semi-autos as well as their Model 12 and 121 "Fieldmaster" pump actions in .22 short.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] Remington's Nylon 66 GS Gallery Special (1962 to 1981) was one of the last .22 short-only rifles made especially for shooting gallery use.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] Winchester produced a variety of different rifles in .22 short, including the 1873 lever action, 1885 single shot (in both low wall and high wall variations), Model 1890, 1906 and 62A pump actions, Model 74 semi-auto, and Model 61 pump action.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] Many of their bolt-action rifles were available on a special-order basis in .22 short.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] Browning/FN also produced their takedown semi-auto in .22 short, on the same John Browning design upon which the Remington Model 24 is based.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] Many of these rifles are now collector's items, particularly the Winchesters, and demand a premium in price over the same rifle chambered in .22 long rifle.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] Many rifles marked ".22 short, long and long rifle" (or ".22 S, L, LR") will not shoot shorts with the same accuracy as they will a long rifle round nor as accurately as a rifle designed for .22 short.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] This is due to the excess chamber length needed to allow chambering of .22 LR cartridges.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] This requires the bullet from a .22 short to travel a short distance before it engages the rifling, which is detrimental to accuracy.
[src:gatling-gun/22-short] In addition, barrels made for .22 short are rifled with a rate of twist of one turn in twenty inches, while barrels made for .22 long rifle have a twist of one turn in sixteen inches.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] The **.30-03 Springfield** (7.62×65mm) was a short-lived cartridge developed by the United States in 1903, to replace the .30-40 Krag in the new Springfield 1903 rifle.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] The .30-03 was also called the .30-45, since it used a 45 grain (2.9 g (0.10 oz)) powder charge; the name was changed to .30-03 to indicate the year of adoption.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] It used a 220 grain (14 g (0.49 oz)) roundnose bullet.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] It was replaced after only three years of service by the .30-06, firing a spitzer bullet that had better ballistic performance.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] The .30-03 was developed to replace the .30-40 Krag cartridge used in the Krag–Jørgensen rifle, which was the first bolt action rifle adopted by the US military, and the first that used smokeless powder.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] A new rifle was designed, using the Mauser as a guide, and a new cartridge was designed for it.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] Initially the *.30-01* cartridge was developed in 1901; also referred to as the .30 ball Model of 1901 - the ".30-01" or "Thick-rim", the .30-01 used a bullet covered by an alloy made from copper and nickel and was the immediate predecessor of the .30-03.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] It was short-lived however, quickly being replaced by the .30-03 cartridge.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] The new cartridge was more powerful, using a 45-grain (2.9 g) charge of smokeless powder, 5 grains (0.3 g) more than the .30-40.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] The bullet was the same, a .30 caliber, 220 grain (14 g) round-nosed jacketed bullet, at a higher velocity of 2,300 feet per second (700 m/s), compared to the 2,000 feet per second (610 m/s) of the .30-40 Krag.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] The new rifle was also the first in a trend of shorter infantry rifles; the 24 in (610 mm) barrel was halfway between the standard infantry rifle and the carbine used by the cavalry, and thus there was no carbine variant of the 1903 rifle.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] The .30-03 cartridge was also a rimless design, which allowed better feeding through the box magazine than the old .30-40 Krag case.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] The Model 1895 Winchester lever-action rifle was offered in .30-03 from 1905, but sold poorly in comparison to the .30-06 chambering offered in 1908.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] Vickers Company in England produced Maxim M1904 machine guns in .30-03 for the US Army from 1908.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] Later M1904 machine guns were produced by Colt in .30-06 and the .30-03 guns were re-chambered for the .30-06.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] In 1903, the Army converted its M1900 Gatling guns in .30 Army to fit the new .30-03 cartridge as the M1903.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] This conversion was principally carried out at the Army's Springfield Armory arsenal repair shops.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] All models of Gatling guns were declared obsolete by the U.S.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] Army in 1911, after 45 years of service.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] The .30-03 cartridge suffered from the start.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] It caused severe erosion of the bore of the rifle, due to the high pressures and temperatures needed to push the heavy bullet to the desired velocity.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] The heavy bullet was also an issue; the 220 grain (14 g) bullet was aerodynamically inefficient and had a very curved trajectory (see external ballistics) so it was not well suited for long-range shots.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] It was also unfashionable since most countries were switching to a 7 or 8 mm cartridge firing a lighter, around 150 grains (9.7 g), spitzer pointed bullet at a higher velocity.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] This gave better energy retention and a flatter trajectory.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] The .30-03 was shortened slightly by 0.046 inches (1.2 mm) in the neck, the powder was reformulated to burn cooler, and the bullet was changed to a 150 grain (9.7 g) spitzer bullet, creating the .30-06 cartridge.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] Since the new .30-06 was shorter than the .30-03, it could fire in 1903 rifles but resulted in poor accuracy.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] The 1903 rifles were all recalled, fitted with the Model of 1905 sights and bayonets, and rechambered for the new .30-06 cartridge.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] This last procedure was done by unscrewing the barrels, milling off the end of each chamber, re-threading the barrels, rechambering them, and screwing them back on the same actions.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] This ended the short life of the .30-03; out of nearly 75,000 made, few original 1903 rifles escaped the conversion to .30-06 (estimates range from 50 to 100 rifles); surviving .30-03 rifles are rare collector's items.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] Even the .30-03 cartridge is a rarity and is found only in collections of rare cartridges.
[src:gatling-gun/30-03] The .270 Winchester cartridge was based on reducing the neck diameter of the .30-03 cartridge case to retain a similar overall length with the same shoulder based on observation of the Chinese military trials of 6.8x57 Mauser in the US.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The **.30-06 Springfield** cartridge (pronounced "thirty-aught-six" /ˈθɜːrti ɔːt sɪks/), **7.62×63mm** in metric notation, and called the **.30 Gov't '06** by Winchester, was introduced to the United States Army in 1906 and later standardized; it remained in military use until the late 1970s.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] In the cartridge's name, ".30" refers to the nominal caliber of the bullet in inches; "06" refers to the year the cartridge was adopted, 1906.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] It replaced the .30-03 Springfield, 6mm Lee Navy, and .30-40 Krag cartridges.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Army's primary rifle and machine gun cartridge for nearly 50 years before being replaced in 1957 by the 7.62×51mm NATO and 5.56×45mm NATO, both of which remain in current U.S. and NATO service.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The cartridge remains a very popular sporting round, with ammunition produced by all major manufacturers.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] In the early-1890s, the U.S. military adopted the smokeless powder .30-40 Krag rimmed cartridge.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The 1894 version of that cartridge used a 220-grain (14 g) round-nose bullet.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Around 1901, the U.S. started developing an experimental rimless cartridge for a Mauser action with a box magazine.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] That led to the 1903 .30-03 Springfield rimless service round that used the same 220-grain (14 g) round-nose bullet as the Krag.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Consequently, the round-nosed U.S. .30-03 service cartridge was falling behind.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] For these reasons, the U.S. military developed a new, lighter cartridge in 1906, the .30-06 Springfield, "cartridge, ball, caliber .30, Model of 1906", or just *M1906*.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The .30-03 case was modified to have a slightly shorter neck to fire a spitzer flat-based 150-grain (9.72 g) bullet that had a ballistic coefficient (G1 BC) of approximately 0.405, a muzzle velocity of 2,700 ft/s (820 m/s), and a muzzle energy of 2,429 ft⋅lbf (3,293 J).
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The cartridge was loaded with military rifle (MR) 21 propellant, and its maximum range was claimed (falsely) to be 4,700 yd (4,300 m).
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The M1903 Springfield rifle, which had been introduced alongside the .30-03 cartridge, was modified to accept the new .30-06 Springfield cartridge.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Modifications to the rifle included shortening the barrel at its breech and resizing the chamber, so that the more tapered bullet would not have to jump too far to reach the rifling.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Other changes to the rifle included the elimination of the troublesome "rod bayonet" of the earlier Springfield rifles.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The M1906 maximum range was originally overstated.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] When the M1906 cartridge was developed, the range tests had been done to only 1,800 yards (1,650 m); distances beyond that were estimated, but the estimate for extreme range was incorrect by almost 40 percent.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The range discrepancy became evident during World War I.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Before the widespread employment of light mortars and artillery, long-range machine gun "barrage" or indirect fires were considered important in U.S. infantry tactics.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] When the U.S. entered World War I, it did not have many machine guns, so it acquired British and French machine guns.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] When those weapons were later replaced with U.S. machine guns firing the M1906 round, the effective range of the barrage was 50 percent less.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Firing tests performed around 1918 at Borden Brook Reservoir (Massachusetts), Miami, and Daytona Beach showed the actual maximum range of the M1906 cartridge to be 3,300 to 3,400 yards (3,020 to 3,110 m).
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Germany, which was using the *S Patrone* (S ball cartridge) loaded with a similar 153-grain (9.9 g) flat-based bullet in its rifles, had apparently confronted and solved the same problem by developing an aerodynamically more refined bullet for long-range machine gun use.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Patrone* was introduced in 1914 and used a 197.5-grain (12.80 g) *s.S. – schweres Spitzgeschoß* (heavy spitzer) boat-tail bullet which had a maximum range of approximately 5,000 m (5,468 yd).
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] This bullet further reduced air resistance in flight, resulting in less rapid downrange deceleration, less lateral drift caused by crosswinds, and significantly greater supersonic and maximum effective range from machine guns and rifles alike.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Additionally, a gilding metal jacket was developed that all but eliminated the metal fouling that plagued the earlier M1906 cartridge.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The loaded round weighed 420 grains (27 g) and its maximum range was approximately 5,500 yd (5,030 m).
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The maximum average pressure (MAP) was 48,000 psi (330.95 MPa).
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The average target radius was specified to be not greater than 4.5 in (11 cm) at 500 yd (457 m) and not greater than 5.5 in (14 cm) at 600 yd (549 m) when fired from a Mann accuracy weapon.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Wartime surplus totaled over two billion rounds of ammunition.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Army regulations called for training use of the oldest ammunition first.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] As a result, the older .30-06 ammunition was expended for training; stocks of .30 M1 ball ammunition were allowed to slowly grow until all of the older M1906 ammunition had been fired.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] By 1936, it was discovered that the maximum range of the .30 M1 ball ammunition with its boat-tailed spitzer bullets was beyond the safety limitations of many military firing ranges.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] An emergency order was made to manufacture quantities of ammunition that matched the external ballistics of the earlier M1906 cartridge as soon as possible.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] A new cartridge was developed in 1938 that was essentially a duplicate of the old M1906 round, but loaded with IMR 4895 propellant and a new flat-based bullet that had a gilding metal jacket and a different lead alloy, and weighed 152 grains (9.85 g) instead of 150 grains (9.72 g).
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] This 1938 pattern cartridge, the cartridge, caliber .30, ball, M2, achieved a muzzle velocity of 2,805 ft/s (855 m/s) and muzzle energy of 2,656 ft⋅lbf (3,601 J).
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The loaded round weighed 416 grains (27.0 g) and its maximum range was approximately 3,450 yd (3,150 m).
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The MAP was 50,000 psi (344.74 MPa) by copper crusher (equivalent to the SAAMI CUP unit).
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The average target radius was specified to be not greater than 6.5 in (16.5 cm) at 500 yd (457 m) and not greater than 7.5 in (19.1 cm) at 600 yd (549 m).
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] It served the United States in both World Wars and in the Korean War, and its last major use was during the Vietnam War.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The Belgian army (ABL) bought the FN Model 1949 rifle in .30-06 caliber (both as a sniper version with telescopic sights and as a general service weapon).
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The Belgian armed forces used the round widely in the Korean war, where the .30-06 caliber FN-49 proved to be a superior weapon in terms of both accuracy and reliability than the American M1 Garand.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The .30-06 FN-49 saw widespread use in the various wars in and around the Belgian Congo.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The 30-06 FN-49 was also sold to the armies of Luxembourg, Indonesia, and Colombia.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Another customer was Brazil where it served the navy.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Large volumes of surplus brass made it the basis for dozens of commercial and wildcat cartridges, as well as being extensively used for reloading.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] In 1908, the Model 1895 Winchester lever-action rifle became the first commercially-produced sporting rifle chambered in .30-06 Springfield.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] It is still a very common round for hunting and is suitable for large game such as bison, sambar deer, and bear, when used at close to medium ranges.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] With "hot" handloads and a rifle capable of handling them, the .30-06 is capable of performance rivaling many magnum cartridges.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] However, when loaded more closely to the original government specs, .30-06 remains within the upper limit of felt recoil most shooters consider tolerable over multiple rounds, unlike the magnums, and is not unnecessarily destructive of meat on game such as deer.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] With appropriate loads, it is suitable for any small or large heavy game.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The .30-06's power and versatility (combined with the availability of surplus firearms chambered for it and demand for commercial ammunition) have kept the round as one of the most popular for hunting in North America.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The .30-06 cartridge was designed when shots of 1,000 yards (914.4 m) were expected.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] In 1906, the original M1906 .30-06 cartridge consisted of a 150 grains (9.7 g), flat-base cupronickel-jacketed-bullet.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] After World War I, the U.S. military needed better long-range performance machine guns.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Based on weapons performance reports from Europe, a streamlined, 173 grains (11.2 g) boattail, gilding-metal bullet was used.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The .30-06 cartridge, with the 173 grains (11.2 g) bullet was called *cartridge, .30, M1 ball*.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The .30-06 cartridge was far more powerful than the smaller Japanese 6.5×50mm Arisaka cartridge and comparable to the Japanese 7.7×58mm Arisaka.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The new M1 ammunition proved to be significantly more accurate than the M1906 round.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] In 1938, the unstained, 150 grains (9.7 g), flat-base bullet combined with the .30-06 case became the M2 ball cartridge.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The M2 ball specifications required 2,740 feet per second (835.2 m/s) minimum velocity, measured 78 feet (24 m) from the muzzle.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] M2 ball was the standard-issue ammunition for military rifles and machine guns until it was replaced by the 7.62×51mm NATO round in 1954.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] For rifle use, M2 ball ammunition proved to be less accurate than the earlier M1 cartridge; even with match rifles, a target group of 5 inches (130 mm) diameter at 200 yards (180 m) using the 150-grain (9.7 g) M2 bullet was considered optimal, and many rifles did not perform nearly as well.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Marine Corps retained stocks of M1 ammunition for use by snipers and trained marksmen throughout the Solomon Islands campaign in the early years of the war.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] In an effort to increase accuracy, some snipers resorted to use of the heavier .30-06 M2 armor-piercing round, a practice that re-emerged during the Korean War.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Others sought out lots of M2 ammunition produced by Denver Ordnance, which had proved to be more accurate than those produced by other wartime ammunition plants when used for sniping at long range.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] With regards to penetration, the M2 AP round can penetrate at least 0.42 in (10.67 mm) of armor steel at 100 yards (91 m).
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Commercially manufactured rifles chambered in .30-06 are popular for hunting.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Current .30-06 factory ammunition varies in bullet weight from 7.1 to 14.3 grams (110 to 220 grains) in solid bullets, and as low as 3.6 grams (55 grains) with the use of a sub-caliber bullet in a sabot.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Loads are available with reduced velocity and pressure as well as increased velocity and pressure for stronger firearms.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The .30-06 remains one of the most popular sporting cartridges in the world.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Many hunting loads have over 3,000 foot-pounds (4,100 J) of energy at the muzzle and use expanding bullets that can deliver rapid energy transfer to targets.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The table above shows typical muzzle velocities available in commercial 30-06 loads along with the maximum .30-06 muzzle velocities reported by several reloading manuals for common bullet weights.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Hodgdon, Nosler, and Barnes report velocities for 24 inches (610 mm) barrels.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Hornady and Speer report velocities for 22 inches (560 mm) barrels.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The data are all for barrels with a twist rate of 1 turn in 10 inches (250 mm) which is needed to stabilize the heaviest bullets.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The higher muzzle velocities reported by Nosler for 165 grains (10.7 g) and heavier bullets use loads employing a slow-burning, double-base powder (Alliant Reloder 22).
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The newer 7.62×51mm NATO/.308 Winchester cartridge offers similar performance to standard military .30-06 loadings in a smaller cartridge.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] One reason that the .30-06 has remained a popular round for so long is that the cartridge is at the upper limit of power that is tolerable to most shooters.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Recoil energy (free recoil) greater than 20 foot-pounds force (27 J) will cause most shooters to develop a serious flinch, and the recoil energy of an 8-pound (3.6 kg) rifle firing a 165-grain (10.7 g) 30-06 bullet at 2,900 feet per second (880 m/s) is 20.1 foot-pounds force (27.3 J).
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Recoil-shy shooters can opt for lighter bullets, such as a 150-grain (9.7 g) bullet.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] In the same 8-pound (3.6 kg) rifle, a 150-grain (9.7 g) bullet at 2,910 feet per second (890 m/s) will only generate 17.6 foot-pounds force (23.9 J) of recoil energy.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Young shooters can start out with even lighter bullets weighing 110, 125, or 130 grains (7.1, 8.1, or 8.4 g).
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The .30-06 Springfield cartridge case can hold 68.2 grains and has a volume of 4.42 millilitres (0.270 in3).
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The exterior shape of the case was designed to promote reliable case feeding and extraction in bolt-action rifles and machine guns alike, under extreme conditions.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Americans define the shoulder angle at alpha/2 = 17.5 degrees.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] According to the official C.I.P. guidelines, the .30-06 Springfield case can handle up to 405 MPa (58,740 psi) piezo pressure.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] In C.I.P.-regulated countries, every rifle cartridge combination has to be proofed at 125% of this maximum C.I.P. pressure to certify for sale to consumers.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The 8×64mm S is the closest European ballistic twin of the .30-06 Springfield.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Although the .30-06 was designed as a military round, it soon caught the attention of big game hunters in the United States.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] This new cartridge offered a flatter trajectory and carried more energy than the popular .30-30 Winchester.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The .30-06 also could be loaded with the then new spitzer designed projectiles, which also contributed to extending the cartridge's performance with respect to other .30 caliber bullets fired from lever action rifles, making it easier to put venison on the table.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] It is a very versatile round that may be loaded with bullets ranging from 110 to 220 grains, which may be effectively stabilized from 1:10" twist barrels.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Thus, the cartridge may be used to hunt animals of different sizes from varmint to moose and even brown bears with adequately constructed heavy bullets.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Since the cartridge may be used for taking all North American big game species it was considered an all-round by hunters and gun writers such as Jack O'Connor, who hunted extensively with it.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] President Theodore Roosevelt took a .30-06 to his famous African Safari along with his son Kermit and Frederick Courteney Selous, proving that the .30-06 could bring down game of any size.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Though not optimal for dangerous game, the .30-06 is adequate for hunting African plains game.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] With 150-grain bullets, the .30-06 Springfield is a perfect option for medium-sized game such as deer and sheep.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Leaving the muzzle at 2950 fps, it gives the hunter a maximum point blank range slightly short of 300 yards.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The .30-06 is also the parent case for many other hunting cartridges such as the .270 Winchester, .25-06 Remington, .280 Remington, .308 Winchester, and .280 Ackley Improved.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] These kind of cartridges are balanced, flat-shooting cartridges that are commonly used for big game hunting of mid-sized species.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Despite the new trend towards high ballistic coefficient cartridges, designed to be used with short-length actions, hunters still praise the .30-06 as it still lists high in the popularity ranking of big game hunting cartridges, and every major gun maker chambers it in at least one of its rifles.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The .30-06 round was replaced by the 7.62×51mm NATO round in 1954.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] However, it remained in limited use in the army reserves and national guard for some time; Frankford Arsenal only stopped production in 1961, and Lake City Army Ammunition Plant was making .30-06 until the late 1970s, with new production batches in 1993 and 2002.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The "T" (Trials) designation is the code number it had when it was under development and testing.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The "M" (Model) designation is the number it received when it was made standard-issue.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Issued bullets before 1934 used the year of adoption as their model number.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The .30-06 (or "caliber .30") cartridge was adopted in 1940 during the beginnings of the Lend-Lease program in anticipation of using American weapons in front-line service.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The British used American-made ammunition during the war, which was designated as *cartridge S.A, .30* to avoid confusing it with their own .303 British service round.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] It was used after the war as belted machinegun ammunition by the Royal Armored Corps and was not declared obsolete until October, 1993.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The "z" after the numeral indicates that it used a nitrocellulose propellant rather than cordite.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Marks of ammunition were originally designated with Roman numerals (i.e., .303 Ball Mark VII), but were replaced with Arabic numerals by 1945 (i.e., .303 Ball MK 7).
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] The .30-06 round was adopted in 1949 for use in American war surplus military aid weapons like the M1 Garand and M1919 medium machinegun.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Military production was from the 1950s to the mid-1960s, while export production to French Union nations lasted until the late 1980s.
[src:gatling-gun/30-06-springfield] Cartridge cases were softer than US specifications to prohibit their being recovered and reloaded by insurgents.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] Since the cartridge it was replacing was the .45-70 Government, the new cartridge was considered *small-bore* at the time.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] The rifle ultimately selected for use by the Army was formally adopted as the M1892 Springfield, better known as the Krag–Jørgensen from the Norwegian designers' names.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] The cartridge was also used in the M1893, M1895, M1897, and M1900 Gatling guns.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] Navy and Marine Corps had adopted limited numbers of smokeless powder and bolt-action rifles, the .30-40 was the first cartridge adopted by the US Army that was designed from the outset for smokeless powder.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] It was patterned after .303 British, to which it is very similar geometrically.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] After a brief experiment with a 230-grain bullet loading, the .30 Army loading was standardized in 1894 using a 220-grain (14 g) metal-jacketed round-nose bullet with 40 gr (2.6 g) of nitrocellulose powder.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] This loading developed a maximum velocity of 2,000 ft/s (610 m/s) in the 30-inch (760 mm) barrel of the Krag rifle, and 1,960 ft/s (600 m/s) in the 22-inch (560 mm) barrel of the Krag carbine.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] Due to its dimensional similarities .303 brass can be annealed and pressed into .30-40 dimensions in a full-length sizing die.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] A converted .303 case will turn out ~2 mm shorter than a factory new .30-40 case, but it is still a viable option for handloaders when new factory brass is scarce.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] The rimmed .30-40 round was also known as .30 Army or .30 U.S.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] Although the .30-40 Krag was the first smokeless powder round adopted by the U.S. military, it retained the "caliber-charge" naming system of earlier black powder cartridges, i.e. a .30-caliber bullet propelled by 40 grains (2.6 g) of smokeless powder.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] The first use of a smokeless powder round by Winchester was a single shot in 30-40, and it was one of only three rounds for which the 1895 Winchester lever action, introduced in 1896, was originally chambered.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] From the outset, the .30-40 cartridge proved popular for hunting and was chambered in a variety of firearms.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] In 1899, a Krag in .30-40 caliber owned by Colorado coal miner John Plute, was used to shoot a world-record Rocky Mountain elk.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] Although Plute never lived to see the record, he gave the antlers to a bar called the Elk Saloon in 1915 to pay his bar tab and died in 1922, 40 years before the record was declared.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] The owners then requested an official score sheet from the Boone and Crockett Club, after scoring the antlers and sending the card back the club didn't believe the results, as it was much larger than the current record at the time.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] So, the owners asked a Colorado game warden to measure the antlers, and the club disbelieved his measurements as well.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] The club said they would only publish the results if they could examine the antlers in person, so in 1962 the antlers were shipped to their headquarters in New York.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] The club measured the antlers at being five feet wide and the base measured a foot around, they declared it a world record which stood from 1962 until 1998 when another elk beat it by only quarter of an inch.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] In October 1899, after reviewing the experiences of the Spanish–American War, U.S.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] Army ordnance authorities developed a new loading for the .30 Army used in the Krag rifle, in an attempt to match the ballistics of the 7×57mm Mauser cartridge employed by Spanish forces in that conflict.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] The new loading increased the muzzle velocity in the rifle version of the Krag to 2,200 ft/s (670 m/s) at 45,000 psi.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] However, once the new loading was issued, reports of cracked locking lugs on service Krags began to surface.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] In March 1900, the remaining stocks of this ammunition (some 3.5 million rounds) were returned to the arsenals, broken down, and reloaded back to the original 2,000 ft/s (610 m/s) specification.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] In 1903, after recommendations from the infantry Small Arms Board, the U.S.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] Army formally adopted a higher-velocity .30-caliber replacement for the .30-40 or .30 Army cartridge.
[src:gatling-gun/30-40-krag] The new cartridge was designated by its year of adoption, the .30-03, although it was only in service for three years before being modified and became the .30-06 Springfield.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] The **.44 Henry**, also known as the **.44 Henry Flat**, the **.44 Rimfire**, the **.44 Long Rimfire**, and the **11x23mmRF** (11x23mm Rimmed) in Europe, is a rimfire rifle and handgun cartridge featuring a .875 in (22.2 mm)-long brass or copper case.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] The original propellant load is 26 to 28 gr (1.68 to 1.81 g; 0.06 to 0.06 oz) of black powder.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] The round has a muzzle velocity of approximately 1,125 ft/s (343 m/s), giving a muzzle energy of 568 foot-pounds (770 joules).
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] The cartridge is named after the intended firearm of use, the Henry rifle, which is in turn named after Benjamin Tyler Henry, the 19th-century American gunsmith who invented both the cartridge and the rifle of that name.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] Henry designed both in his spare time while he was the foreman of the New Haven Arms Company, and was granted a US patent for his creations on October 16, 1860.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] While it was not the first repeating rifle, it was one of the first successful designs (alongside the Spencer rifle), and it provided the basis for the iconic Winchester rifle, and all modern lever-action rifles.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] Other breechloaders of the time often relied on a simple, separate percussion cap for ignition, just like a typical muzzleloader of the era, and often used paper or linen cartridge cases, which provided no obturation, or sealing of the breech against the expanding gases (such as the Sharps rifle).
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] Some utilized self-contained primers, but still lacked metallic cases (the Dreyse "needle gun").
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] While these one-shot breechloading weapons were great improvements over the muzzleloader, it required the adoption of the self-contained metallic case before repeaters could become viable weapons.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] The .44 Henry was an early self-contained metallic cartridge, and was one of the main reasons for the ultimate success of the Henry rifle.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] The cartridge's original 200-grain bullet had a flat nose.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] A bullet with a more pointed nose was later used in order to decrease aerodynamic drag and increase range.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] Modern comparisons to the .44 Henry rifle's ballistics would include such large-bore handgun cartridges as the 200 gr .45 ACP, and 200 gr .44 Special, or black powder "cowboy loads" of early rifle cartridges like the .44-40 WCF and .45 Colt.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] Due to the vast advances in propellant and metallurgy technology, these latter can nearly achieve the Henry Rifle's velocity from a handgun, and do not even require the long barrel of a rifle to give equivalent velocity.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] By modern standards, the resulting effective range for the .44 Henry fired from a rifle on military targets or small to medium game would be up to 200 yards.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] However, when it was introduced in 1860, standards such as effective range to ensure a humane kill and a hit in a vital area were far more lax, and most hunters were accustomed to hunting game at short ranges in any case.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] Such performance was not unusual or remarkable, and the idea of weapons capable of engaging a target at hundreds of yards was generally reserved for dedicated, long-barreled target rifles and trained shooters.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] For a typical infantry or cavalry soldier, or hunter, a rifle accurate at 100 yd (91 m) was sufficient.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] The ability to fire 16 rounds before reloading made the Henry's lack of long range capability even less of an issue.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] The .44 Henry cartridge was used most notably in the Henry Model 1860 repeating rifle.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] This rifle was first used in the American Civil War, mainly by Union cavalry troops, although only in very limited numbers.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] It was also used by the very few Confederate troops who managed to capture one of these rifles along with a supply of ammunition, which was impossible to find in the Confederate south; a few were even purchased by wealthy Confederates.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] After the Civil War, the Henry cartridge was used in the Winchester Model 1866 rifles during the Franco-Prussian War 1870/71 by the French and by the Ottoman Empire during the Russo-Turkish War (1877–1878).
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] In civilian models, Winchester Model 1866 rifles and carbines, Smith & Wesson No.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] 3 Revolvers, Colt Model 1860 Army long cylinder conversion and the Colt Model 1871-72 "Open Top" revolvers were available in .44 Henry.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] From 1875 until 1880, Colt produced the Model 1873 Single Action Army in .44 Henry to accommodate owners of Henry Model 1860 and Winchester Model 1866 rifles and carbines.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] The cartridge cases were originally made from copper, and later brass.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] The cartridge was still commercially made into the 1930s.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] The .44 Henry cartridge was perfected by George R.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] Patent 120403, assigned to the Winchester Repeating Arms Company on October 31, 1871.
[src:gatling-gun/44-henry] It has as its object the use of swaged and lubricated projectiles of greater perfection in shape.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The **Gatling gun** is a rapid-firing multiple-barrel firearm invented in 1861 by Richard Jordan Gatling of North Carolina.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] It is an early machine gun and a forerunner of the modern electric motor-driven rotary cannon.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The Gatling gun is centered on a cyclic multi-barrel design which facilitated cooling and synchronized the firing-reloading sequence.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] This configuration eliminated the need for a single reciprocating bolt design and allowed higher rates of fire to be achieved without the barrels overheating quickly.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] One of the best-known early rapid-firearms, the Gatling gun saw occasional use by the Union Army during the American Civil War, which was the first time it was employed in combat.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] It was later used in numerous military conflicts, including the Boshin War, the Anglo-Zulu War, and the assault on San Juan Hill during the Spanish–American War.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] It was also used by the Pennsylvania militia in episodes of the Great Railroad Strike of 1877, specifically in Pittsburgh.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Gatling guns were also mounted aboard ships.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The Gatling gun is operated by a hand-crank mechanism, with six barrels revolving around a central shaft (although some models had as many as ten).
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Each barrel fires once per revolution at about the same position.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The barrels, a carrier, and a lock cylinder were separate and all mounted on a solid plate revolving around a central shaft, mounted on an oblong fixed frame.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The carrier was grooved and the lock cylinder was drilled with holes corresponding to the barrels.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The casing was partitioned, and through this opening, the barrel shaft was journaled.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] In front of the casing was a cam with spiral surfaces.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The cam imparted a reciprocating motion to the locks when the gun rotated.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Also in the casing was a cocking ring with projections to cock and fire the gun.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Each barrel had a single lock, working in the lock cylinder on a line with the barrel.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The lock cylinder was encased and joined to the frame.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Early models had a fibrous matting stuffed in among the barrels, which could be soaked with water to cool the barrels down.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Later models eliminated the matting jacketing as being unnecessary.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Cartridges, held in a hopper, dropped individually into the grooves of the carrier.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The lock was simultaneously forced by the cam to move forward and load the cartridge, and when the cam was at its highest point, the cocking ring freed the lock and fired the cartridge.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] After the cartridge was fired the continuing action of the cam drew back the lock bringing with it the spent casing which then dropped to the ground.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The grouped barrel concept had been explored by inventors since the 18th century, but poor engineering and the lack of a unitary cartridge made previous designs unsuccessful.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The initial Gatling gun design used self-contained, reloadable steel cylinders with a chamber holding a ball and black-powder charge, and a percussion cap on one end.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] As the barrels rotated, these steel cylinders dropped into place, were fired, and were then ejected from the gun.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The innovative features of the Gatling gun were its independent firing mechanism for each barrel and the simultaneous action of the locks, barrels, carrier, and breech.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The ammunition that Gatling eventually implemented was a paper cartridge charged with black powder and primed with a percussion cap because self-contained brass cartridges were not yet fully developed and available.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The shells were gravity-fed into the breech through a hopper or simple box "magazine" with an unsprung gravity follower on top of the gun.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Each barrel had its own firing mechanism.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Despite self-contained brass cartridges replacing the paper cartridge in the 1860s, it was only in the Model 1881 that Gatling switched to the 'Bruce'-style feed system (U.S.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] While one row was being fed into the gun, the other could be reloaded, thus allowing sustained fire.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] By 1886, the gun was capable of firing more than 400 rounds per minute.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The smallest-caliber gun also had a Broadwell drum feed in place of the curved box of the other guns.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Broadwell, an agent for Gatling's company, comprised twenty stacks of rounds arranged around a central axis, like the spokes of a wheel, each holding twenty cartridges with the bullet noses oriented toward the central axis.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] As each stack emptied, the drum was manually rotated to bring a new stack into use until all 400 rounds had been fired.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] A more common variant had 240 rounds in twenty stands of fifteen.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] By 1893, the Gatling was adapted to take the new .30 Army smokeless cartridge.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The new M1893 guns featured six barrels, later increased to ten barrels, and were capable of a maximum (initial) rate of fire of 800–900 rounds per minute, though 600 rpm was recommended for continuous fire.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Gatling later used examples of the M1893 powered by electric motor and belt to drive the crank.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Tests demonstrated the electric Gatling could fire bursts of up to 1,500 rpm.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The M1893, with minor revisions, became the M1895, and 94 guns were produced for the U.S.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Four M1895 Gatlings under Lieutenant John H.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Parker saw considerable combat during the Santiago campaign in Cuba in 1898.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The M1895 was designed to accept only the Bruce feeder.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] All previous models were unpainted, but the M1895 was painted olive drab green, with some parts left blued.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Model 1900 was very similar to Model 1895 but with only a few components finished in O.D. green.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] All Gatling Models 1895-1903 could be mounted on an armored field carriage.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] In 1903, the Army converted its M1900 guns from .30 Army to fit the new .30-03 cartridge (standardized for the M1903 Springfield rifle) as the M1903.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] All models of Gatling guns were declared obsolete by the U.S. military in 1911, after 45 years of service.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The original Gatling gun was a field weapon that used multiple rotating barrels turned by a hand crank, and firing loose (no links or belt) metal cartridge ammunition using a gravity feed system from a hopper.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The Gatling gun's innovation lay in the use of multiple barrels to limit overheating, a rotating mechanism, and a gravity-feed reloading system, which allowed unskilled operators to achieve a relatively high rate of fire of 200 rounds per minute.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Although the first Gatling gun was capable of firing continuously, it required a person to crank it and so it was not a true automatic weapon.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The Maxim gun, invented and patented in 1883, was the first true fully-automatic weapon making use of the fired projectile's recoil force to reload the weapon.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Nonetheless, the Gatling gun represented a huge leap in firearm technology.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Before the Gatling gun, the only weapons available to military forces that could fire many projectiles in a short period of time were mass-firing volley weapons, like the Belgian and French mitrailleuse of the 1860s and 1870s, and field cannons firing canister shot, much like an upsized shotgun.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The latter was widely used during and after the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Although the maximum rate of fire was increased by firing multiple projectiles simultaneously, those weapons still needed to be reloaded after each discharge, which for multi-barrel systems like the *mitrailleuse* was cumbersome and time-consuming.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] That negated much of the advantage of their high rate of fire per discharge by making them much less powerful on the battlefield.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] In comparison, the Gatling gun offered a rapid and continuous rate of fire without having to be manually reloaded by opening the breech.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Early multi-barrel guns were approximately the size and weight of artillery pieces and were often perceived as a replacement for cannons firing grapeshot or canister shot.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Compared with earlier weapons such as the *mitrailleuse,* which required manual reloading, the Gatling gun was more reliable and easier to operate and had a lower, but continuous rate of fire.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The large wheels required to move these guns around required a high firing position, which increased the vulnerability of their crews.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Sustained firing of black powder cartridges generated a cloud of smoke, making concealment impossible until smokeless powder became available in the late 19th century.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] When operators were firing Gatling guns against troops of industrialized nations, they were at risk, being vulnerable to artillery they could not reach and snipers they could not see.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The Gatling gun was designed by the American inventor Richard J.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Gatling in 1861 and patented on November 4, 1862.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Gatling wrote that he created it to reduce the size of armies and so reduce the number of deaths by combat and disease.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The US Army adopted Gatling guns in several calibers, including .42 caliber, .45-70, .50 caliber, 1 inch, and (M1893 and later) .30 Army, with conversions of M1900 weapons to .30-03 and .30-06.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The .45-70 weapon was also mounted on some US Navy ships of the 1880s and 1890s.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The British manufacturer James George Accles, previously employed by Colt 1867–1886, developed a modified Gatling gun circa 1888 known as the Accles Machine Gun.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Circa 1895, the American Ordnance Company acquired the rights to manufacture and distribute this weapon in the Americas.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] It was trialed by the US Navy in December 1895, and was said to be the only weapon to complete the trial out of five competing weapons, but was apparently not adopted by US forces.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The Gatling gun was first used in warfare during the American Civil War.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Twelve of the guns were purchased personally by Union commanders and used in the trenches during the Siege of Petersburg, Virginia (June 1864—April 1865).
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Eight other Gatling guns were fitted on gunboats.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The gun was not accepted by the American Army until 1866 when a sales representative of the manufacturing company demonstrated it in combat.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] On July 17, 1863, Gatling guns were purportedly used to overawe New York anti-draft rioters.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Two were brought by a Pennsylvania National Guard unit from Philadelphia to use against strikers in Pittsburgh.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Gatling guns were famously *not* used at the Battle of the Little Bighorn, also known as "Custer's Last Stand," when General George Armstrong Custer chose not to bring Gatling guns with his main force.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] In April 1867, a Gatling gun was purchased for the Argentine Army by Interior Minister Domingo F.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Sarmiento under instructions from President Bartolomé Mitre.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Captain Luis Germán Astete of the Peruvian Navy took with him dozens of Gatling guns from the United States to Peru in December 1879 during the Peru-Chile War of the Pacific.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Gatling guns were used by the Peruvian Navy and Army, especially in the Battle of Tacna (May 1880) and the Battle of San Juan (January 1881) against the invading Chilean Army.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] In 1888, the *SS Ozama* smuggled a number of Gatling guns into Haiti.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] In 1907, Gatling guns were used by Nicaragua in the battle of Namasique, largely manned by American mercenaries.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Gatling guns were kept in store by coal companies and used during the Battle of Blair Mountain in 1921.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] On September 1, a group of striking miners stole one of the guns and assaulted a valley called Craddock Fork near the town of Lake.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Opposing forces fought back with a machine gun, but after three hours of heavy fire, their weapon jammed.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The miners surged forward and briefly broke the defensive line, but were repulsed by another machine gun nest located further up the ridge.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] According to Ellis, the Russians were amongst the first to realize the potential of machine guns, testing two Gatlings in 1865 and promptly ordering twenty for the Imperial Russian Army, eventually obtaining a license to build them locally.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] By 1876, the Russians had 400 Gatlings organized in eight batteries.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] However, historical writer Chris McNab stated that the Russians had been introduced to the Gatling in 1871, not 1865, when Colonel Aleksandr Pavlovich Gorloff was given a demonstration, and impressed by what he saw, ordered 400 Gatlings for the Imperial Army.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Both accounts agree that these guns, known in Russia as *Gorloffs* first saw action during the Russo-Turkish War (1877–1878), where they were effectively used at the Battle of Nikopol and the Siege of Plevna.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The *Gorloff* gun was also used during the Russian conquest of Central Asia to repel Turkmen cavalry charges.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The Gatling gun was used most successfully to expand European colonial empires by defeating indigenous warriors mounting massed attacks, including the Zulu, the Bedouin, and the Mahdists.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The British Army first deployed the Gatling gun in 1873-74 during the Anglo-Ashanti wars, and extensively during the last actions of the 1879 Anglo-Zulu war.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The Royal Navy used Gatling guns during the 1882 Anglo-Egyptian War.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Gatling guns were used by Egyptian forces both on sea and land and saw combat in Sudan and Abyssinia.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Isma'il Pasha ordered 120 Colt 1865 six-barrel Gatling guns; after being convinced by Shahine Pasha who witnessed Gatling gun trials at Shoeburyness in 1866.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] In 1872 a few ''camel'' guns were purchased, these were smaller and used a tripod instead of the carriage.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] During the Siege of Khartoum an Egyptian Gatling gun aided by a telescope was able to target Sudanese artillery crews from a distance of 2,000 yards.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Gatling guns were imported by some states in Nigeria.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] They were used during the Kalabari Civil War of 1879–83, the Abbi House bought one from King Jaja of Opobo and it may have been used in canoe warfare.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The Ijesha used a Gatling gun against the Ibadan during the early 1880s.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] In 1882 the Bonny used a Gatling gun during an attack on New Calabar.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] By 1880, the Siam kingdom, now Thailand, had imported an unknown number of Gatlings.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] By 1885 the kingdom had a Gatling Gun regiment of 600 men; those weapons were possibly used in the Haw Wars.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] They were also seen among Prince Bigit's escort in 1886.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The Korean Empire possessed a number of Gatlings.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Six had been imported in 1884, by 1891 it had a battery of fourteen guns and in 1894 the army's two American drilled regiments had as many as 40 Gatlings and practiced regularly (Supposedly because the noise pleased Emperor Gojong).
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Some of them were deployed to defend the approaches of the capital during the Donghak Rebellion, but there is no evidence they saw combat.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Howard of the Connecticut National Guard had an interest in the company manufacturing Gatling guns.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] In 1885 Howard brought a personally owned Gatling gun to the North-West Territories of Canada in what is now, since 1905, the Province of Saskatchewan for use with the Canadian military against Métis and First Nations rebels during the North-West Rebellion of 1885 led by Louis Riel.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Gatling guns were used successfully by the U.S.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Army during the Spanish–American War in 1898.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] A four-gun battery of Model 1895 ten-barrel Gatling guns chambered in .30 Army, made by Colt, was formed as part of a separate detachment led by Lieutenant John "Gatling Gun" Parker.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The detachment proved very effective, supporting the advance of American forces at the Battle of San Juan Hill.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Three of the Gatlings with swivel mountings were used with great success against the Spanish defenders.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] During the American charge up San Juan and Kettle hills, the three guns fired a total of 18,000 rounds in 8+1⁄2 minutes (an average of over 700 rounds per minute per gun of continuous fire) against Spanish troop positions along the crest of both hills, causing significant casualties.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Despite this successful deployment, the Gatling's weight and cumbersome artillery carriage hindered its ability to keep up with infantry forces over uneven terrain, particularly in Cuba, where roads were often little more than jungle footpaths.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Marines had been issued the modern tripod-mounted M1895 Colt–Browning machine gun using the 6mm Lee Navy round, which they employed to defeat the Spanish infantry at the battle of Cuzco Wells.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Army during the Philippine–American War.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] One such instance was during the Battle of San Jacinto (1899) (Spanish: *Batalla de San Jacinto*) which was fought on November 11, 1899, in San Jacinto in the Philippines, between Philippine Republican Army soldiers and American troops.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The Gatling's weight and artillery carriage hindered its ability to keep up with American troops over uneven terrain, especially in the Philippines, where movement outside the cities was hindered by dense forests and steep mountain paths.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] After the Gatling gun was phased out and replaced by newer recoil or gas-operated weapons, the approach of using multiple externally powered rotating barrels fell into disuse for many decades.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] However, some examples were developed during the interwar years, but only existed as prototypes or were rarely used.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] The concept resurfaced after World War II with the development of the Minigun and the M61 Vulcan in particular for use in aircraft over reciprocating bolt autocannons which are more prone to jamming in high g environments.
[src:gatling-gun/gatling-gun] Multiple other rotating barrel firearms were built from the late 20th century to the present, the largest of them being the 30mm GAU-8 Avenger autocannon as used on the Fairchild Republic A-10 Thunderbolt II.
